Padding

    If the number of bytes in the original data is not a multiple of three, Base64 adds padding with the = character to ensure the encoded output is a multiple of four characters.

Example

For example, if you encode the string "cat" (which is 3 bytes):

    The Base64 encoded output is Y2F0.
    If you had a 1-byte input (e.g., A), it would be encoded as QQ==, where == is padding to make the total length a multiple of four.

This table helps you understand how any binary data can be encoded into a Base64 string, making it suitable for transmission in text-based formats.